06164nam a22008295i 9780674275683DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742756837 a10.4159/97806742756832doi  a(DE-B1597)624080  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aPS805.F43bG78 2022 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a306.442/61073223/eng/202203241 aGruesz, Kirsten Silva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCotton Mather’s Spanish Lessons :bA Story of Language, Race, and Belonging in the Early Americas /cKirsten Silva Gruesz. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Style -- tI. Introduction: The First Spanish Imprint in English America -- tII. The Global Designs of a Creole Family -- tIII. Telling the Future of America Mexicana -- tIV. From Language Encounters to Language Rights -- tV. Becoming a Spanish Indian -- tVI. Teaching by Catechism and Conversation -- tVII. Books as Keys to the Spanish Tongue -- tVIII. Impressing the Word in Exotic Types -- tIX. Racial Fears on Eighteenth-Century Frontiers -- tX. The Shipwreck of the Family Design -- tXI. Coda: Colonial Lessons in Latinidad -- tXII. Transcription and Translation of Cotton Mather’s La Fe del Christiano (1699) -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping history of linguistic and colonial encounter in the early Americas, anchored by the unlikely story of how Boston’s most famous Puritan came to write the first Spanish-language publication in the English New World. The Boston minister Cotton Mather was the first English colonial to refer to himself as an American. He was also the first to author a Spanish-language publication: La Fe del Christiano (The Faith of the Christian), a Protestant tract intended to evangelize readers across the Spanish Americas. Kirsten Silva Gruesz explores the conditions that produced La Fe del Christiano, from the intimate story of the “Spanish Indian” servants in Mather’s household, to the fragile business of printing and bookselling, to the fraught overlaps of race, ethnicity, and language that remain foundational to ideas of Latina/o/x belonging in the United States today. Mather’s Spanish project exemplifies New England’s entanglement within a partially Spanish Catholic, largely indigenous New World. British Americans viewed Spanish not only as a set of linguistic practices, but also as the hallmark of a rival empire and a nascent racial-ethnic category. Guided by Mather’s tract, Gruesz explores English settlers’ turbulent contacts with the people they called “Spanish Indians,” as well as with Black and local native peoples. Tracing colonial encounters from Boston to Mexico, Florida, and the Caribbean, she argues that language learning was intimately tied with the formation of new peoples. Even as Spanish has become the de facto second language of the United States, the story of La Fe del Christiano remains timely and illuminating, locating the roots of latinidad in the colonial system of the early Americas. Cotton Mather’s Spanish Lessons reinvents our understanding of a key colonial intellectual, revealing notions about language and the construction of race that endure to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristian literature, Spanishy18th century. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aEthnicityzAmericaxHistoryy18th century. 0aEthnicityzAmericaxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aEvangelistic workzAmericaxHistoryy18th century. 0aLiterature and racezAmericaxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colo